docs.abstract: Beijing and Washington both hinted that they could make concessions to strike a deal on trade.
docs.snippet: Beijing and Washington both hinted that they could make concessions to strike a deal on trade.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks briefly clawed back into positive territory for the year on Wednesday, as Beijing and Washington both hinted that they could make concessions to strike a deal on trade.

headline.main: Markets Rise After Positive Signals Between U.S. and China
headline.print_headline: Markets Rise on Hopes for Trade Détente

byline.original: By Amie Tsang and Matt Phillips

docs.abstract: New details are emerging about the long, symbiotic and at times troubled relationship between the president and his loyal German bank.
docs.snippet: New details are emerging about the long, symbiotic and at times troubled relationship between the president and his loyal German bank.
docs.lead_paragraph: For nearly two decades, Donald J. Trump relied on Deutsche Bank to lend to him when other banks wouldn’t. Deutsche Bank, eager to expand in the United States, made a decision to repeatedly take a risk on him.

headline.main: Deutsche Bank and Trump: $2 Billion in Loans and a Wary Board

docs.abstract: Spain’s Socialist prime minister pushed through a 22 percent increase in the minimum wage law. As salaries increase, businesses fear an erosion in jobs.
docs.snippet: Spain’s Socialist prime minister pushed through a 22 percent increase in the minimum wage law. As salaries increase, businesses fear an erosion in jobs.
docs.lead_paragraph: MADRID — As Spain grapples with a turbulent political crisis, one of Europe’s last Socialist governments may soon fall amid the rise of a new nationalism in the country. But whatever the outcome, Prime Minister Pedro Sánchez is leaving behind a signature legacy: a record increase in the minimum wage.

headline.main: Spain’s Minimum Wage Just Jumped. The Debate Is Continuing.
headline.print_headline: Spain’s Minimum Wage Has Surged. So Has Debate.

docs.abstract: Less than a year after the country ended a multibillion-euro international bailout, property buyers from China and Russia are helping to mend its economy.
docs.snippet: Less than a year after the country ended a multibillion-euro international bailout, property buyers from China and Russia are helping to mend its economy.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATHENS — Less than a year after Greece emerged from a multibillion-euro international bailout, Athens is witnessing an investor boom. Hip new hotels with Acropolis views are dotting the skyline. Construction workers are tearing into dwellings owned by Greeks needing cash and converting them swiftly to short-term rentals, Airbnbs or fancy new homes for foreigners.

headline.main: In Greece, an Economic Revival Fueled by ‘Golden Visas’ and Tourism
headline.print_headline: Investors and Tourists Fuel a Greek Revival, at a Cost

docs.abstract: Though not charged with a crime, the powerful auto executive could stay in detention even longer under Japanese law, likely in spare conditions.
docs.snippet: Though not charged with a crime, the powerful auto executive could stay in detention even longer under Japanese law, likely in spare conditions.
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — Carlos Ghosn, one of the world’s most powerful car industry leaders, will be detained for 10 more days as prosecutors investigate accusations of financial misconduct against him, and French and Japanese officials prepare to meet over the case.

headline.main: Nissan’s Ghosn to Spend at Least 10 More Days in Custody
headline.print_headline: Nissan’s Ghosn to Spend at Least 10 More Days in Japanese Custody

byline.original: By Motoko Rich and Liz Alderman

docs.abstract: Tax breaks, land deals and cheap energy have spurred cryptocurrency mining in Georgia, which wants to be a digital data leader.
docs.snippet: Tax breaks, land deals and cheap energy have spurred cryptocurrency mining in Georgia, which wants to be a digital data leader.
docs.lead_paragraph: TBILISI, Georgia — For three years, a windowless warehouse on the edge of town has been whirring with enough energy to power nearly 50,000 homes. Day and night, the warehouse, and dozens of cargo containers in a windswept valley, are generating Bitcoin, the cryptocurrency that has created a virtual gold rush in the former Soviet republic of Georgia.

headline.main: Despite Bitcoin’s Dive, a Former Soviet Republic Is Still Betting Big on It
headline.print_headline: A Bitcoin Gold Rush in the Caucasus

docs.abstract: Tsunekazu Takeda faces scrutiny in France over payments that prosecutors say were bribes to help Tokyo win hosting rights for the 2020 Summer Games.
docs.snippet: Tsunekazu Takeda faces scrutiny in France over payments that prosecutors say were bribes to help Tokyo win hosting rights for the 2020 Summer Games.
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — The head of Japan’s Olympic Committee said on Tuesday that he would step down at the end of his term this summer — a decision that comes as he faces a French corruption investigation into how Tokyo was chosen to host next year’s Summer Games.

headline.main: Japan’s Olympic Chief to Step Down Amid Corruption Investigation

docs.abstract: The Japanese authorities suspect breach of trust by the former Nissan chief, who denied wrongdoing and called the arrest “outrageous and arbitrary.”
docs.snippet: The Japanese authorities suspect breach of trust by the former Nissan chief, who denied wrongdoing and called the arrest “outrageous and arbitrary.”
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — Carlos Ghosn, the embattled former chief of the Nissan-Renault-Mitsubishi auto alliance, was arrested for a fourth time on Thursday as he faces accusations of using company funds for his personal ends.

headline.main: Carlos Ghosn Arrested in Tokyo Over New Accusations
headline.print_headline: Ghosn Arrested  For 4th Time,  On Accusations Of Fund Misuse

docs.abstract: The company, facing weaker U.S. sales, issued its second downward revision in two months as it attempts to move on since Carlos Ghosn’s arrest.
docs.snippet: The company, facing weaker U.S. sales, issued its second downward revision in two months as it attempts to move on since Carlos Ghosn’s arrest.
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — Nissan said on Wednesday that it expected its annual profit to be much lower than expected, a fresh blow to a company reeling from the arrest of its former top executive Carlos Ghosn.

headline.main: Nissan Warns Investors of a 45 Percent Drop in Profit
headline.print_headline: Nissan Warns Investors of a 45% Drop in Profits

docs.abstract: The Japanese automaker’s chief executive told the shareholders, “We have to admit that there was a significant problem with our corporate governance.”
docs.snippet: The Japanese automaker’s chief executive told the shareholders, “We have to admit that there was a significant problem with our corporate governance.”
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — Nissan shareholders voted on Monday to remove Carlos Ghosn from the company’s board, severing one of its last ties to an executive who once was hailed as the automaker’s savior.

headline.main: Carlos Ghosn, Once Nissan’s Savior, Is Voted Off the Board
headline.print_headline: Nissan’s Savior, Now Behind Bars, Is Voted Off Board
